The paper deals with sparse signal recovery, which is a topic that falls under several sub-categories in computer science. However, the use of linear systems of equations and optimization algorithms suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT), Machine Learning (cs.LG), Signal Processing (cs.SP), Numerical Analysis (cs.NA), or Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-categories. Among these, cs.IT and cs.LG are the most likely sub-categories, as they both deal with optimization problems and signal processing. The use of weighted $\ell_1$ minimization and the comparison with the iterative re-weighted $\ell_1$ (IRWL1) minimization algorithm also suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.SP sub-category. The use of simulations and computational cost analysis suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.NA sub-category. Finally, the use of sparse recovery techniques suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.SI sub-category, although this is less likely than the other sub-categories mentioned.
